      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\\\README.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: <p align=\"center\">\n2:   <img src=\"docs/assets/lampforge-banner.svg\" alt=\"LAMPForge Banner\" width=\"600\" />\n3: </p>\n4: \n5: <h1 align=\"center\">🔥 LAMPForge - Cognitive Engineering Platform</h1>\n6: \n7: <p align=\"center\">\n8:   <strong>AI-powered scaffolding · Live code generation · In-browser execution</strong>\n9:   <br />\n10:   <em>Eliminating infrastructure friction for A-Level Digital Technology students</em>\n11: </p>\n12: \n13: <p align=\"center\">\n14:   <a href=\"https://pedagogical-development-environment-sdtp.lovable.app\">Live Demo</a> ·\n15:   <a href=\"docs/ARCHITECTURE.md\">Architecture</a> ·\n16:   <a href=\"docs/USER-JOURNEYS.md\">User Journeys</a> ·\n17:   <a href=\"docs/RATIONALE.md\">Design Rationale</a> ·\n18:   <a href=\"docs/CI-CD-PIPELINE.md\">CI/CD Pipeline</a> ·\n19:   <a href=\"docs/ROADMAP.md\">Roadmap</a>\n20: </p>\n21: \n22: ---\n23: \n24: ## Table of Contents\n25: \n26: - [What is LAMPForge?](#what-is-lampforge)\n27: - [The Problem](#the-problem)\n28: - [The Solution](#the-solution)\n29: - [Platform Screenshots](#platform-screenshots)\n30: - [System Architecture](#system-architecture)\n31: - [The 5-Family Taxonomy](#the-5-family-taxonomy)\n32: - [Scaffold Levels](#scaffold-levels)\n33: - [AI Pipeline](#ai-pipeline)\n34: - [Technology Stack](#technology-stack)\n35: - [Project Structure](#project-structure)\n36: - [Getting Started](#getting-started)\n37: - [Quick Reference](#quick-reference)\n38: - [Recent Changes](#recent-changes)\n39: - [IDE Surface](#ide-surface-3-tier-fallback-chain)\n40: - [Documentation Index](#documentation-index)\n41: - [License](#license)\n42: \n43: ---\n44: \n45: ## What is LAMPForge?\n46: \n47: LAMPForge is a **Pedagogical Development Environment (PDE)** - a cognitive engineering platform that transforms how A-Level Digital Technology students learn database-driven web development. Instead of spending hours wrestling with XAMPP, phpMyAdmin, and configuration files, students **declare their intent in plain English** and LAMPForge translates it into:\n48: \n49: - ✅ Normalised database schemas (1NF → 3NF+)\n50: - ✅ PHP CRUD operations (from `mysqli` to PDO with CSRF protection)\n51: - ✅ Bootstrap-powered HTML forms\n52: - ✅ Live-editable code in a VS Code-style IDE\n53: - ✅ An in-browser SQL workbench with real SQLite execution\n54: - ✅ Automatic SDLC evidence logging for coursework portfolios\n55: \n56: ---\n57: \n58: ## The Problem\n59: \n60: > *\"Students spend 70% of their coursework time on infrastructure setup and only 30% on actual learning.\"*\n61: \n62: The WJEC/Eduqas Digital Technology Unit 4 requires students to build a LAMP-stack web application demonstrating the full Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC). The current landscape presents critical barriers:\n63: \n64: | Barrier | Impact |\n65: |---------|--------|\n66: | **XAMPP/WAMP configuration** | Hours lost to `localhost` issues, port conflicts, PHP version mismatches |\n67: | **SQL syntax errors** | Students abandon complex schemas, defaulting to flat 1NF tables |\n68: | **PHP security patterns** | SQL injection, XSS, CSRF - concepts too advanced for the time allotted |\n69: | **Evidence collection** | Manual screenshots, copy-paste of SQL - tedious and error-prone |\n70: | **Grade ceiling** | Without scaffolding, most students plateau at Grade C |\n71: \n72: ---\n73: \n74: ## The Solution\n75: \n76: LAMPForge inverts the paradigm: **Intent → Architecture → Code → Evidence**\n77: \n78: ```text\n79: ┌─────────────────┐     ┌──────────────────┐     ┌──────────────────┐     ┌──────────────────┐\n80: │  Student types   │────▶│  AI generates    │────▶│  Code appears    │────▶│  Evidence logged  │\n81: │  plain English   │     │  blueprint       │     │  in IDE          │     │  automatically    │\n82: │  intent          │     │  (entities,      │     │  (SQL + PHP +    │     │  (SDLC timeline)  │\n83: │                  │     │   relationships, │     │   HTML forms)    │     │                   │\n84: │                  │     │   CRUD ops)      │     │                  │     │                   │\n85: └─────────────────┘     └──────────────────┘     └──────────────────┘     └──────────────────┘\n86: ```\n87: \n88: ---\n89: \n90: ## Platform Screenshots\n91: \n92: ### Landing Page - Intent Declaration\n93: \n94: The landing page is the entry point. Students describe what they want to build in natural language, select their target scaffold level, and hit \"Forge It.\"\n95: \n96: ![LAMPForge Landing Page](docs/assets/screenshot-landing.png)\n97: \n98: *The hero section with scaffold level selector (Exploratory → RAD 2.0), intent textarea, and template gallery.*\n99: \n100: ### Unified PDE - Development Environment\n101: \n102: The PDE provides a full IDE experience with architecture canvas, code editor, CLI, SQL workbench, and evidence panel - all in one view.\n103: \n104: ![LAMPForge PDE](docs/assets/screenshot-pde.png)\n105: \n106: *The unified PDE showing the architecture canvas (left), Code-OSS editor (right), CLI with ASCII banner (bottom), and panel toggle bar (top).*\n107: \n108: ### Architecture Canvas\n109: \n110: A visual React Flow canvas where entities and relationships are rendered as interactive nodes. Students can add entities, connect them with relationships, and see the schema evolve in real-time.\n111: \n112: ![LAMPForge Canvas](docs/assets/screenshot-canvas.png)\n113: \n114: *The canvas with Entity and Transaction nodes, StackBlitz WebContainer editor, and the LAMPForge CLI terminal.*\n115: \n116: ### SQL Workbench\n117: \n118: A fully functional SQL workbench powered by `sql.js` (SQLite compiled to WebAssembly). Students can execute queries against their generated schema without any server-side infrastructure.\n119: \n120: ![LAMPForge SQL Workbench](docs/assets/screenshot-workbench.png)\n121: \n122: *Schema explorer sidebar, Monaco-powered query editor, and tabular results grid.*\n123: \n124: ### Evidence & SDLC Logger\n125: \n126: Automatic evidence capture across the full SDLC. Every action - schema generation, query execution, code editing - is timestamped and categorised by stage.\n127: \n128: ![LAMPForge Evidence Logger](docs/assets/screenshot-evidence.png)\n129: \n130: *Timeline view with SDLC stage badges (Analysis, Design, Implementation, Testing, Evaluation) and event cards.*\n131: \n132: ---\n133: \n134: ## System Architecture\n135: \n136: ```mermaid\n137: graph TB\n138:     subgraph \"Client - Browser\"\n139:         LP[Landing Page<br/>Intent Declaration]\n140:         PDE[Unified PDE]\n141:         WB[SQL Workbench]\n142:         EV[Evidence Logger]\n143:         \n144:         subgraph \"PDE Panels\"\n145:             CV[Architecture Canvas<br/>React Flow]\n146:             IDE[Code-OSS / StackBlitz<br/>WebContainer]\n147:             CLI[CLI Panel<br/>Command Registry]\n148:             SQL[SQL Workbench Panel<br/>sql.js / SQLite WASM]\n149:             EVP[Evidence Panel<br/>Timeline View]\n150:         end\n151:     end\n152: \n153:     subgraph \"AI Pipeline\"\n154:         AR[Arch-Router<br/>Intent Classification]\n155:         ONNX[Browser Native (ONNX)<br/>Router + First Inference]\n156:         FL[Foundry Local<br/>OpenAI-compatible endpoint]\n157:         CL[Cloud Fallbacks<br/>Groq → Cerebras]\n158:     end\n159: \n160:     subgraph \"Code Generation\"\n161:         DDL[DDL Generator<br/>MySQL Schema]\n162:         PHP[PHP CRUD Generator<br/>4 Scaffold Levels]\n163:         HTML[HTML Form Generator<br/>Bootstrap 5]\n164:     end\n165: \n166:     LP -->|\"Intent + Scaffold Level\"| ONNX\n167:     ONNX -->|\"Route + Blueprint (success)\"| PDE\n168:     ONNX -->|\"Fallback\"| AR\n169:     AR -->|\"Fallback\"| FL\n170:     FL -->|\"Fallback\"| CL\n171:     FL -->|\"Blueprint (local success)\"| PDE\n172:     CL -->|\"Blueprint (cloud fallback success)\"| PDE\n173:     PDE --> CV\n174:     PDE --> IDE\n175:     PDE --> CLI\n176:     PDE --> SQL\n177:     PDE --> EVP\n178: \n179:     PDE -->|\"Blueprint\"| DDL\n180:     PDE -->|\"Blueprint\"| PHP\n181:     PDE -->|\"Blueprint\"| HTML\n182:     DDL -->|\"schema.sql\"| IDE\n183:     PHP -->|\"*.php\"| IDE\n184:     HTML -->|\"*.html\"| IDE\n185: ```\n186: \n187: ### Key Architectural Decisions\n188: \n189: | Decision | Rationale |\n190: |----------|-----------|\n191: | **In-browser SQLite via WASM** | Zero infrastructure - no MySQL server needed |\n192: | **StackBlitz WebContainer** | Full Node.js runtime in browser - no backend hosting |\n193: | **OpenVSCode Server (Gitpod)** | Primary IDE via 3-tier fallback chain (OpenVSCode → Code-OSS → StackBlitz) |\n194: | **BroadcastChannel API** | Panel undocking to separate browser tabs |\n195: | **Zod schema validation** | Type-safe blueprint validation at runtime |\n196: | **Tiered AI fallback** | ONNX-first (router + first inference) → Foundry Local → Groq → Cerebras |\n197: \n198: ---\n199: \n200: ## The 5-Family Taxonomy\n201: \n202: LAMPForge organises all concepts into five cognitive families, each with a colour-coded identity:\n203: \n204: | Family | Colour | Icon | Purpose |\n205: |--------|--------|------|---------|\n206: | **Blueprint** | 🔵 Blue | `#3B82F6` | Entity design, schema, ERD, normalisation |\n207: | **Plumbing** | 🟢 Green | `#22C55E` | Connectivity - relationships, FKs, joins, state |\n208: | **Transaction** | 🟠 Orange | `#F59E0B` | Logic - CRUD operations, sessions, validation |\n209: | **Core** | 🔴 Red | `#EF4444` | Provisioning - code generation, build, deploy |\n210: | **Oracle** | 🟣 Purple | `#A855F7` | AI inference, analysis, suggestions, feedback |\n211: \n212: This taxonomy maps directly to the visual language of the canvas nodes, CLI output coloring, and evidence log badges.\n213: \n214: ---\n215: \n216: ## Scaffold Levels\n217: \n218: LAMPForge adapts its output to four scaffold levels, each targeting a different WJEC grade band:\n219: \n220: | Level | Grade Target | Normalisation | PHP Style | Security | Features |\n221: |-------|-------------|---------------|-----------|----------|----------|\n222: | **Exploratory** | E/D | 1NF (flat) | Raw `mysqli` | None | Basic forms, no FK |\n223: | **Competent** | C/B | 2NF | `mysqli` + escaping | Input sanitisation | Bootstrap, FK constraints |\n224: | **Exemplary** | A/A* | 3NF | PDO prepared statements | CSRF tokens, sessions | Indexes, audit columns, junction tables |\n225: | **RAD 2.0** | No ceiling | 3NF+ | PDO + soft deletes | Full security stack | Pagination, search, HMR preview |\n226: \n227: ### How Scaffold Levels Affect Code Generation\n228: \n229: ```mermaid\n230: graph LR\n231:     subgraph \"Exploratory\"\n232:         E1[\"1NF Tables\"]\n233:         E2[\"Raw mysqli\"]\n234:         E3[\"Plain HTML\"]\n235:     end\n236:     \n237:     subgraph \"Competent\"\n238:         C1[\"2NF + FKs\"]\n239:         C2[\"mysqli_real_escape\"]\n240:         C3[\"Bootstrap Forms\"]\n241:     end\n242:     \n243:     subgraph \"Exemplary\"\n244:         X1[\"3NF + Indexes\"]\n245:         X2[\"PDO + CSRF\"]\n246:         X3[\"Bootstrap + Alerts\"]\n247:     end\n248:     \n249:     subgraph \"RAD 2.0\"\n250:         R1[\"3NF+ + Soft Delete\"]\n251:         R2[\"PDO + Pagination\"]\n252:         R3[\"Vite HMR Preview\"]\n253:     end\n254: \n255:     E1 --> C1 --> X1 --> R1\n256:     E2 --> C2 --> X2 --> R2\n257:     E3 --> C3 --> X3 --> R3\n258: ```\n259: \n260: ---\n261: \n262: ## AI Pipeline\n263: \n264: The AI pipeline uses a three-stage architecture with ONNX-first inference:\n265: \n266: ### Stage 1: ONNX Router (Intent Classification)\n267: \n268: The browser-native ONNX path leads route classification and computes a first local route decision:\n269: - `schema_generation` - Complex multi-entity schemas\n270: - `simple_crud` - Single-entity CRUD apps\n271: - `ecommerce` - Transactional systems with carts/orders\n272: \n273: If ONNX routing is unavailable, the local Arch-Router is used as fallback.\n274: \n275: ### Stage 2: Blueprint Generation\n276: \n277: Four strategies, tried in order:\n278: \n279: 1. **Browser Native (ONNX)**: first blueprint generation attempt\n280: 2. **Foundry Local** (offline-capable): OpenAI-compatible local endpoint with tool-calling\n281: 3. **Cloud Fallback 1**: Groq API\n282: 4. **Cloud Fallback 2**: Cerebras API\n283: \n284: ### Stage 3: Validation\n285: \n286: The generated blueprint is validated against the `ForgeBlueprintSchema` (Zod) with cross-reference checks:\n287: - All relationship endpoints reference existing entities\n288: - All transaction entities exist\n289: - All page routes reference valid entities\n290: \n291: ```mermaid\n292: sequenceDiagram\n293:     participant S as Student\n294:     participant LP as Landing Page\n295:     participant O as ONNX\n296:     participant AR as Arch-Router\n297:     participant FL as Foundry Local\n298:     participant G as Groq\n299:     participant C as Cerebras\n300:     participant V as Validator\n301:     participant PDE as PDE\n302: \n303:     S->>LP: \"I need a library system...\"\n304:     LP->>O: Classify + generate blueprint (ONNX first)\n305:     alt ONNX succeeds\n306:         O-->>LP: ForgeBlueprint JSON\n307:     else ONNX unavailable/invalid\n308:         LP->>AR: Classify intent (fallback)\n309:         AR-->>LP: route: \"schema_generation\"\n310:         LP->>FL: Generate blueprint (local)\n311:         alt Foundry Local available\n312:             FL-->>LP: ForgeBlueprint JSON\n313:         else Local unavailable\n314:             LP->>G: Generate blueprint (cloud primary)\n315:             alt Groq succeeds\n316:                 G-->>LP: ForgeBlueprint JSON\n317:             else Groq fails\n318:                 LP->>C: Generate blueprint (cloud secondary)\n319:                 C-->>LP: ForgeBlueprint JSON\n320:             end\n321:         end\n322:     end\n323:     LP->>V: Validate against Zod schema\n324:     V-->>LP: Validated blueprint\n325:     LP->>PDE: Navigate with blueprint\n326:     PDE->>PDE: Populate canvas + generate files\n327: ```\n328: \n329: ---\n330: \n331: ## Technology Stack\n332: \n333: ### Frontend\n334: | Technology | Purpose |\n335: |-----------|---------|\n336: | **React 18** | Component framework |\n337: | **Vite** | Build tool with HMR |\n338: | **TypeScript** | Type safety |\n339: | **Tailwind CSS** | Utility-first styling with custom design tokens |\n340: | **shadcn/ui** | Accessible component library |\n341: | **React Flow (`@xyflow/react`)** | Architecture canvas with interactive nodes |\n342: | **Monaco Editor** | Code editing (via `@monaco-editor/react`) |\n343: | **sql.js** | SQLite compiled to WebAssembly for in-browser SQL |\n344: | **StackBlitz SDK** | WebContainer for in-browser Node.js runtime |\n345: | **Zod** | Runtime schema validation |\n346: \n347: ### Backend / AI Integration\n348: | Technology | Purpose |\n349: |-----------|---------|\n350: | **Foundry Local** | Preferred local OpenAI-compatible inference endpoint |\n351: | **Groq API** | Primary cloud blueprint-generation fallback |\n352: | **Cerebras API** | Secondary cloud blueprint-generation fallback |\n353: | **ONNX Runtime Web** | In-browser router + first blueprint attempt before local/cloud fallbacks |\n354: | **Supabase Edge Functions** | Optional serverless integration available in `supabase/functions` |\n355: \n356: ### Design System\n357: | Token | Light | Dark |\n358: |-------|-------|------|\n359: | `--forge-blueprint` | `hsl(210, 100%, 56%)` | `hsl(210, 100%, 60%)` |\n360: | `--forge-plumbing` | `hsl(142, 72%, 45%)` | `hsl(142, 72%, 50%)` |\n361: | `--forge-transaction` | `hsl(32, 95%, 55%)` | `hsl(32, 95%, 60%)` |\n362: | `--forge-core` | `hsl(0, 72%, 51%)` | `hsl(0, 72%, 55%)` |\n363: | `--forge-oracle` | `hsl(270, 70%, 60%)` | `hsl(270, 70%, 65%)` |\n364: \n365: ---\n366: \n367: ## Project Structure\n368: \n369: This repository follows the standard open-protocol layout - the same pattern used by OpenAPI, GraphQL, and Kubernetes.\n370: \n371: ```text\n372: forge-flow-learn/\n373: │\n374: ├── spec/                          # Protocol specification (source of truth)\n375: │   ├── SPECIFICATION.md           # Every field - type, default, description, example\n376: │   ├── GRAMMAR.md                 # Complete EBNF formal grammar\n377: │   ├── SCHEMA.json                # Draft 2020-12 JSON Schema (VS Code compatible)\n378: │   ├── LIFECYCLE.md               # 9-stage lifecycle with Mermaid sequence diagrams\n379: │   ├── FINOPS.md                  # Cost model, enforcement, JSONL ledger format\n380: │   └── SECURITY.md                # 127.0.0.1 binding, credential gen, DNS rebinding\n381: │\n382: ├── sdk/                           # TypeScript reference implementation\n383: │   ├── forge-protocol.ts          # Zod schema + parseForgeFile() + validateForgeFile()\n384: │   ├── forge-finops.ts            # FinOpsLedger + FinOpsGuard\n385: │   ├── forge-ai.ts                # AI cascade router (ONNX → local → cloud)\n386: │   ├── forge-protocol-loader.ts   # Config resolution: URL param → storage → default\n387: │   ├── forge-types.ts             # Shared TypeScript types (ForgeBlueprint etc.)\n388: │   ├── forge-config.ts            # Config persistence helpers\n389: │   ├── forge-logger.ts            # Structured log emitter\n390: │   ├── forge-onnx.ts              # Browser-native ONNX inference wrapper\n391: │   └── forge-tokenizer.ts         # Token counting for FinOps budget tracking\n392: │\n393: ├── examples/                      # Valid .forge files for real programmes\n394: │   ├── minimal.forge              # Two required fields only\n395: │   ├── wjec-unit4.forge           # WJEC A2 Digital Technology Unit 4\n396: │   ├── aws-restart.forge          # AWS re/Start cloud retraining\n397: │   ├── code-institute.forge       # Code Institute full-stack diploma\n398: │   ├── multi-stack-mern.forge     # MERN stack variant\n399: │   └── air-gapped.forge           # Zero-cloud, local inference only\n400: │\n401: ├── cli/                           # Command-line tooling\n402: │   ├── forge-cli.mjs              # Main CLI entry point\n403: │   ├── commands/                  # Command implementations\n404: │   │   ├── init.mjs               # Interactive .forge generator (terminal wizard)\n405: │   │   ├── validate.mjs           # Schema validation against spec/SCHEMA.json\n406: │   │   ├── preview.mjs            # Preview generated SQL/PHP/HTML code\n407: │   │   └── examples.mjs           # List and copy example .forge files\n408: │   ├── package.json               # npm metadata (installable as @andiekobbietks/forge-cli)\n409: │   └── README.md                  # CLI documentation\n410: │\n411: ├── docs/                          # GitHub Pages documentation site\n412: │   ├── index.html                 # Landing page + protocol overview\n413: │   ├── specification.html         # Full field-by-field spec reference\n414: │   ├── schema.html                # JSON Schema reference + VS Code setup\n415: │   ├── finops.html                # FinOps governance reference\n416: │   ├── implementors.html          # Build a .forge-compatible runtime\n417: │   ├── examples.html              # Annotated example gallery\n418: │   ├── styles.css                 # Dark/light theme stylesheet\n419: │   ├── script.js                  # Active-section tracking + copy buttons\n420: │   └── assets/                    # Screenshots and SVG diagrams\n421: │\n422: ├── src/                           # Playground - React/Vite app (LAMPForge PDE)\n423: │   ├── pages/                     # App routes\n424: │   │   ├── LandingPage.tsx        # Intent declaration + scaffold selector\n425: │   │   ├── PDEPage.tsx            # Unified PDE with all panels\n426: │   │   ├── CanvasPage.tsx         # Architecture canvas (React Flow)\n427: │   │   ├── WorkbenchPage.tsx      # SQL workbench\n428: │   │   ├── WizardPage.tsx         # .forge wizard (guided config builder)\n429: │   │   └── EvidencePage.tsx       # SDLC evidence timeline\n430: │   ├── components/                # React UI components\n431: │   └── lib/                       # Non-forge app utilities\n432: │       ├── sql-generator.ts       # DDL + PHP + HTML code generators\n433: │       ├── pde-channel.ts         # BroadcastChannel for panel undocking\n434: │       ├── vscode-bridge.ts       # PostMessage protocol for Code-OSS\n435: │       └── webcontainer-project.ts # StackBlitz project builder\n436: │\n437: ├── runtime/                       # Supervisor runtime manifests\n438: │   ├── manifest.schema.json       # JSON Schema for runtime manifests\n439: │   ├── supervisor-api.yaml        # OpenAPI spec for Supervisor API\n440: │   └── registry/index.json        # Default provider registry\n441: │\n442: └── supabase/\n443:     └── functions/forge-schema/    # Edge function: AI blueprint generation\n444: ```\n445: \n446: ### The four-layer model\n447: \n448: ```text\n449:                   GitHub Pages (docs/)\n450:                         │\n451:               ┌─────────┼─────────┐\n452:               │         │         │\n453:            spec/     examples/   sdk/\n454:         (protocol)  (.forge      (TypeScript\n455:                      files)       runtime)\n456:               │\n457:               │\n458:            src/\n459:         (playground - \n460:          React PDE app)\n461: ```\n462: \n463: The `spec/` folder is the canonical source of truth.\n464: The `sdk/` folder is the executable implementation of that spec.\n465: The `docs/` folder is the human interface to both.\n466: The `src/` folder is a working playground that consumes the SDK.\n467: \n468: ---\n469: \n470: ## Getting Started\n471: \n472: ### Prerequisites\n473: \n474: - Node.js 18+ (recommended: use [nvm](https://github.com/nvm-sh/nvm))\n475: - npm or bun\n476: \n477: ### Installation\n478: \n479: ```bash\n480: # Clone the repository\n481: git clone <YOUR_GIT_URL>\n482: cd lampforge\n483: \n484: # Install dependencies\n485: npm install\n486: \n487: # Start the development server\n488: npm run dev\n489: ```\n490: \n491: ### Usage\n492: \n493: 1. Navigate to `http://localhost:8080`\n494: 2. Select a **scaffold level** (Exploratory → RAD 2.0)\n495: 3. Type your intent: *\"I need a multi-user library system with book checkout and overdue tracking\"*\n496: 4. Click **Forge It** 🔥\n497: 5. The PDE opens with your generated schema, PHP CRUD code, and HTML forms\n498: 6. Use the **SQL Workbench** to execute queries against your schema\n499: 7. The **Evidence Log** captures everything automatically\n500: \n501: ### Optional: Local AI (Offline Mode)\n502: \n503: For offline blueprint generation, install [Foundry Local](https://github.com/microsoft/foundry) or [Ollama](https://ollama.ai):\n504: \n505: ```bash\n506: # Foundry Local\n507: foundry model run phi-4-mini --port 5273\n508: \n509: # Or Ollama\n510: ollama run phi4-mini\n511: ```\n512: \n513: LAMPForge automatically detects local endpoints and uses them before falling back to the cloud.\n514: \n515: ---\n516: \n517: ## Quick Reference\n518: \n519: ### Common Commands\n520: \n521: | Command | Description |\n522: |---------|-------------|\n523: | `npm run dev` | Start development server on port 8080 |\n524: | `npm run build` | Production build to `dist/` |\n525: | `npm run lint` | Run ESLint (0 errors expected) |\n526: | `npm run preview` | Preview production build locally |\n527: \n528: ### VS Code Setup\n529: \n530: After cloning, ensure these extensions are configured:\n531: \n532: 1. **Tailwind CSS IntelliSense** - If you see `hoist-at-import` warnings:\n533:   - The project uses `postcss-import` to handle this\n534:   - Restart IntelliSense: `Cmd/Ctrl + Shift + P` → \"Tailwind CSS: Restart IntelliSense Server\"\n535: \n536: 2. **ESLint** - The config excludes vendor files (`dev-dist/`, `public/ort*.js`)\n537: \n538: ### Troubleshooting\n539: \n540: | Issue | Solution |\n541: |-------|----------|\n542: | Tailwind IntelliSense not working | Restart IntelliSense server or reload VS Code window |\n543: | ESLint errors in vendor files | These are excluded in `eslint.config.js` - run `npm run lint` to verify |\n544: | Build fails with CSS errors | Ensure `postcss-import` is installed: `npm install` |\n545: | ONNX models not loading | Models are loaded on-demand from `public/` - check network tab |\n546: \n547: For detailed troubleshooting, see [docs/DEPENDENCIES.md](docs/DEPENDENCIES.md#common-issues--fixes).\n548: \n549: ---\n550: \n551: ## Recent Changes\n552: \n553: ### Now (Latest Update)\n554: \n555: - Integrated ONNX Runtime assets and local AI inference support for blueprint generation.\n556: - Added/expanded Forge framework modules across the PDE, including AI pipeline, ONNX helpers, SQL/code generation, CLI surface, and IDE bridge utilities.\n557: - Introduced and updated key UI pages and panels (Landing, PDE, Canvas, Workbench, Evidence, and Admin IDE config flows).\n558: - Expanded documentation and assets (architecture, rationale, user journeys, CI/CD, benchmark methodology, and screenshots).\n559: \n560: ### Previous Day (2026-03-05)\n561: \n562: - No additional commits were recorded between 2026-03-05 and the 2026-03-06 update window.\n563: \n564: ### Last 3 Weeks (Recent Repository Window)\n565: \n566: - Repository history in this window is represented by the 2026-03-06 feature integration commit:\n567:  - `0ea23cb` - *feat: Integrate ONNX Runtime for local AI capabilities and introduce new Forge framework components and UI pages.*\n568: \n569: ---\n570: \n571: ## IDE Surface: 3-Tier Fallback Chain\n572: \n573: LAMPForge uses **Gitpod's OpenVSCode Server** as its primary IDE, with a 3-tier fallback chain:\n574: \n575: ```mermaid\n576: graph LR\n577:     T1[\"Tier 1: OpenVSCode Server\n578:     (Docker / Binary / WebContainer)\"] -->|\"unreachable?\"| T2[\"Tier 2: Static Assets\n579:     /pde/index.html\"]\n580:     T2 -->|\"404?\"| T3[\"Tier 3: StackBlitz\n581:     WebContainer SDK\"]\n582: ```\n583: \n584: Configure the IDE at `/admin/ide-config`. See [docs/CI-CD-PIPELINE.md](docs/CI-CD-PIPELINE.md) for deployment options.\n585: \n586: ---\n587: \n588: ## Sovereign Documentation: Doc-as-Code\n589: \n590: LAMPForge follows a **Doc-as-Code** philosophy. Documentation isn't just a manual; it's a technical asset that lives alongside the logic it describes.\n591: \n592: ### Why Documentation Matters\n593: 1. **Insight Preservation**: High-value \"Golden Standard\" patterns (like our Zero-Infrastructure sync or Deterministic Seed generation) often live \"invisibly\" in the code. Documentation makes these moats visible to future team members.\n594: 2. **Pedagogical Integrity**: As a cognitive engineering platform, our code *must* match our pedagogy. Documentation acts as the formal bridge between \"Logic\" and \"Learning.\"\n595: 3. **Nomenclature Governance**: We maintain a strict taxonomy (e.g., the transition from `forge-forge` to `forge-core`) to ensure the system is mathematically and orthographically optimized for the learner.\n596: \n597: ---\n598: \n599: ## Documentation Index\n600: \n601: | [**ARCHITECTURE.md**](docs/ARCHITECTURE.md) | System architecture, component relationships, data flow |\n602: | [**SOVEREIGN_ARCHITECTURE.md**](docs/SOVEREIGN_ARCHITECTURE_INSIGHTS.md) | **[NEW]** Zero-Infrastructure & Hardware-Abstraction insights |\n603: | [**SOVEREIGN_SCENARIOS.md**](docs/SOVEREIGN_SCENARIOS.md) | **[NEW]** The \"We Asked\" user stories driving the architecture |\n604: | [**DETERMINISTIC_PEDAGOGY.md**](docs/DETERMINISTIC_PEDAGOGY_PROTOCOL.md) | **[NEW]** Deterministic Evidence & PRNG logic |\n605: | [**NOMENCLATURE_EVOLUTION.md**](docs/NOMENCLATURE_EVOLUTION.md) | **[NEW]** Semantic rationale: `forge-forge` → `forge-core` |\n606: | [**RATIONALE.md**](docs/RATIONALE.md) | Design rationale from first thoughts to final implementation |\n607: | [**USER-JOURNEYS.md**](docs/USER-JOURNEYS.md) | User journey maps for students, teachers, and the RAEng panel |\n608: | [**CI-CD-PIPELINE.md**](docs/CI-CD-PIPELINE.md) | Sovereign CI/CD pipeline setup and configuration |\n609: | [**FIVE-FAMILY-TAXONOMY.md**](docs/FIVE-FAMILY-TAXONOMY.md) | The 5-Family cognitive taxonomy deep-dive |\n610: | [**DISTRIBUTED_MESH.md**](docs/DISTRIBUTED_MESH_VISION.md) | **[NEW]** \"Halo LAN\" & P2P Mesh network vision |\n611: | [**PLATFORM_IDENTITY.md**](docs/PLATFORM_IDENTITY.md) | **[NEW]** Protocol history, SDTP definition, and Nomenclature |\n612: | [**BC_HISTORY.md**](docs/BROADCAST_CHANNEL_HISTORY.md) | **[NEW]** Historical background of our \"Local Bus\" sync |\n613: | [**SCIENCE_OF_SNAPPINESS.md**](docs/SCIENCE_OF_SNAPPINESS.md) | **[NEW]** MoSCoW constraints for <100ms IDE native latency |\n614: | [**SOVEREIGN_MCP_IDENTITY.md**](docs/SOVEREIGN_MCP_IDENTITY.md) | **[NEW]** Decentralized Identity Membrane & ZKP for MCP |\n615: | [**COGNITIVE_TAXONOMY_PROTOCOL.md**](docs/COGNITIVE_TAXONOMY_PROTOCOL.md) | **[NEW]** The Visual Grammar of Code (Assistive Identity) |\n616: \n617: ---\n618: \n619: ## The SDTP Protocol\n620: \n621: This repository contains the reference implementation of the **Software-Defined Training Protocol (SDTP)** - an open protocol specification for declarative, cost-governed, curriculum-aligned learning environments.\n622: \n623: ### What SDTP Delivers\n624: \n625: | Capability | Description |\n626: |------------|-------------|\n627: | **Declarative Configuration** | A single `.forge` file defines the entire learning environment - curriculum, infrastructure, FinOps, pedagogy |\n628: | **Constitutional FinOps** | Cost governance embedded in the protocol, not bolted on. Budgets are hard limits, not suggestions |\n629: | **Browser-Native PDE** | Full development environment runs in the browser. No Docker, no server, no install required |\n630: | **Local-First AI** | Inference cascade prefers on-device models (ONNX, Foundry) before falling back to cloud |\n631: | **Curriculum Alignment** | Built for WJEC A2, AWS re/Start, Code Institute, and custom programmes |\n632: | **Evidence Capture** | Automatic SDLC evidence logging for coursework portfolios and compliance |\n633: | **Multi-Stack Support** | LAMP, WAMP, MERN, Django, HONC - same protocol, different stacks |\n634: \n635: ### The Protocol Layers\n636: \n637: ```text\n638: ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n639: │  LAYER 4: DOCUMENTATION (sdtp.forge-protocol)              │\n640: │  Public-facing specification, guides, and examples          │\n641: ├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n642: │  LAYER 3: PDE (Pedagogical Development Environment)        │\n643: │  Browser-native IDE with curriculum-aligned panels          │\n644: ├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n645: │  LAYER 2: SDK (TypeScript Reference Implementation)        │\n646: │  Parsers, validators, code generators, AI cascade           │\n647: ├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n648: │  LAYER 1: SPECIFICATION (spec/)                            │\n649: │  Formal protocol definition - the source of truth           │\n650: └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n651: ```\n652: \n653: ---\n654: \n655: ## Site Map: sdtp.forge-protocol\n656: \n657: The following sitemap describes the planned documentation site at `sdtp.forge-protocol` (domain pending).\n658: \n659: ### Primary Navigation\n660: \n661: | Path | Page | Content |\n662: |------|------|---------|\n663: | `/` | **Home** | Protocol overview, value proposition, quick start guide, hero demo |\n664: | `/specification` | **Specification** | Complete field-by-field reference for `.forge` files - types, defaults, constraints |\n665: | `/schema` | **Schema Reference** | JSON Schema (Draft 2020-12), VS Code integration guide, validation examples |\n666: | `/finops` | **FinOps Governance** | Budget constraints, inference providers, alerts, kill switches, cost accounting |\n667: | `/roadmap` | **Roadmap** | Phased delivery plan, RAEng evidence map, dependency graph, doc-as-code policy |\n668: \n669: ### Reference Section\n670: \n671: | Path | Page | Content |\n672: |------|------|---------|\n673: | `/specification#protocol` | **protocol** | Version declaration, parser selection, compatibility rules |\n674: | `/specification#intent` | **intent** | Human-readable learning intent, evidence panel display |\n675: | `/specification#curriculum` | **curriculum** | Provider mapping (WJEC, AWS, Code Institute), unit references, assessment alignment |\n676: | `/specification#runtime` | **runtime** | Deployment targets (local/codespaces/cloud), stack selection (LAMP/MERN/Django) |\n677: | `/specification#features` | **runtime.features** | Workbench panels, optional tooling, modular PDE composition |\n678: | `/specification#browser-native` | **Browser-Native PDE** | Zero-install architecture, deployment tiers, progressive enhancement |\n679: | `/specification#finops` | **finops** | Budget caps, provider governance, alert thresholds, accounting model |\n680: | `/specification#pedagogy` | **pedagogy** | Scaffold levels (Exploratory → Exemplary), hint systems, error explanations |\n681: | `/specification#versioning` | **versioning** | Semantic versioning policy, deprecation rules, migration guides |\n682: | `/specification#extensions` | **extensions** | Extension points, custom stacks, third-party integrations |\n683: | `/specification#inference` | **inference cascade** | ONNX → Foundry → Groq → Cerebras fallback chain, token budgeting |\n684: | `/specification#session` | **session model** | Session lifecycle, state persistence, multi-user isolation |\n685: \n686: ### FinOps Section\n687: \n688: | Path | Page | Content |\n689: |------|------|---------|\n690: | `/finops#what-is-finops` | **What is FinOps?** | Discipline definition, core principles, FinOps Foundation origins |\n691: | `/finops#before-finops` | **Before FinOps** | DevOps era context, cloud cost chaos, the problem SDTP solves |\n692: | `/finops#origins` | **Origins & Timeline** | 2006–2026 timeline, key figures (J.R. Storment, Mike Fuller), perfect storm analysis |\n693: | `/finops#why-finops` | **Why FinOps in .forge?** | The gap .forge bridges, three guarantees (Predictable, Bounded, Visible) |\n694: | `/finops#constitutional` | **Constitutional FinOps** | Embedded governance, constitutional hierarchy, Anthropic parallel |\n695: | `/finops#budget` | **Budget Constraints** | `max_monthly_cloud`, `max_inference_calls`, currency settings |\n696: | `/finops#providers` | **Inference Providers** | Provider matrix (local/cloud), routing preferences, blocked providers |\n697: | `/finops#alerts` | **Alerts & Kill Switch** | `warn_at`, `kill_at`, notification channels, HTTP 402 behaviour |\n698: | `/finops#accounting` | **Cost Accounting** | Ledger format, what gets logged, audit trail structure |\n699: | `/finops#education` | **Education Context** | First-generation students, Welsh schools, Hwb platform, provider comparison |\n700: \n701: ### Guides Section\n702: \n703: | Path | Page | Content |\n704: |------|------|---------|\n705: | `/implementors` | **Implementors Guide** | Build a `.forge`-compatible runtime, conformance checklist, test suite |\n706: | `/examples` | **Examples** | Annotated `.forge` files for WJEC, AWS re/Start, Code Institute, air-gapped |\n707: | `/getting-started` | **Getting Started** | 5-minute quickstart, first `.forge` file, PDE walkthrough |\n708: | `/cli` | **CLI Reference** | `forge init`, `forge validate`, `forge preview`, `forge examples` |\n709: \n710: ### Advanced Topics\n711: \n712: | Path | Page | Content |\n713: |------|------|---------|\n714: | `/architecture` | **Architecture** | System components, data flow diagrams, integration points |\n715: | `/ai-cascade` | **AI Cascade** | Inference routing logic, provider fallbacks, token estimation |\n716: | `/evidence` | **Evidence Capture** | SDLC stages, screenshot automation, export formats |\n717: | `/security` | **Security Model** | 127.0.0.1 binding, credential management, DNS rebinding protection |\n718: \n719: ### R&D (Internal, Not Public)\n720: \n721: | Path | Page | Content |\n722: |------|------|---------|\n723: | `/internal/strategic-vision` | **Strategic FinOps Vision** | Policy-as-code, TimesFM forecasting, carbon-aware, quality-per-watt |\n724: | `/internal/browser-native` | **Browser-Native Architecture** | PHP-WASM, wa-sqlite, OPFS, Service Worker implementation |\n725: | `/internal/green-computing` | **Green Computing** | Carbon accounting, environmental sustainability, net-zero AI |\n726: | `/internal/constitutional-finops` | **Constitutional FinOps Intel** | Anthropic parallel, strategic positioning, claim defense |\n727: | `/internal/devcontainer-deep-dive` | **Devcontainer Deep Dive** | AWS re/Start, WJEC LAMP/WAMP, ecosystem tools, distribution models |\n728: \n729: ---\n730: \n731: ## What Lives in This Repository\n732: \n733: ```text\n734: forge-flow-learn/\n735: │\n736: ├── spec/                          # PROTOCOL SPECIFICATION\n737: │   ├── SPECIFICATION.md           # Every field - type, default, description\n738: │   ├── GRAMMAR.md                 # Complete EBNF formal grammar\n739: │   ├── SCHEMA.json                # JSON Schema (VS Code compatible)\n740: │   ├── LIFECYCLE.md               # 9-stage lifecycle diagrams\n741: │   ├── FINOPS.md                  # Cost model and enforcement\n742: │   └── SECURITY.md                # Security requirements\n743: │\n744: ├── sdk/                           # TYPESCRIPT SDK\n745: │   ├── forge-protocol.ts          # Zod schema + parser + validator\n746: │   ├── forge-finops.ts            # FinOpsLedger + FinOpsGuard\n747: │   ├── forge-ai.ts                # AI cascade router\n748: │   └── ...                        # Additional SDK modules\n749: │\n750: ├── cli/                           # COMMAND-LINE TOOLS\n751: │   ├── forge-cli.mjs              # Main CLI entry\n752: │   └── commands/                  # init, validate, preview, examples\n753: │\n754: ├── docs/                          # PUBLIC DOCUMENTATION (GitHub Pages)\n755: │   ├── index.html                 # Landing page\n756: │   ├── specification.html         # Protocol reference\n757: │   ├── finops.html                # FinOps governance\n758: │   ├── roadmap.html               # Feature roadmap\n759: │   └── ...                        # Additional pages\n760: │\n761: ├── examples/                      # SAMPLE .forge FILES\n762: │   ├── wjec-unit4.forge           # WJEC A2 Digital Technology\n763: │   ├── aws-restart.forge          # AWS re/Start programme\n764: │   └── ...                        # Additional examples\n765: │\n766: ├── src/                           # PDE PLAYGROUND (React/Vite)\n767: │   ├── pages/                     # App routes\n768: │   ├── components/                # UI components\n769: │   └── lib/                       # Utilities\n770: │\n771: ├── RandD/                         # R&D DOCUMENTATION\n772: │   ├── strategic_finops_vision.md # Advanced FinOps capabilities\n773: │   ├── browser_native_pde_architecture.md # WebAssembly PDE\n774: │   ├── finops_explainer_and_rationale.md # FinOps deep dive\n775: │   └── ...                        # Additional R&D docs\n776: │\n777: ├── internal/                      # INTERNAL DOCUMENTATION\n778: │   └── docs-private/              # Not for public release\n779: │       ├── green_computing_thought_leadership.md\n780: │       ├── constitutional_finops_intel.md\n781: │       ├── devcontainer_pde_deep_dive.md\n782: │       └── roadmap.html           # Extended internal roadmap\n783: │\n784: └── runtime/                       # RUNTIME MANIFESTS\n785:     ├── manifest.schema.json       # Runtime manifest schema\n786:     ├── supervisor-api.yaml        # Supervisor OpenAPI spec\n787:     └── registry/index.json        # Provider registry\n788: ```\n789: \n790: ---\n791: \n792: ## License\n793: \n794: This project is part of an academic coursework submission for WJEC/Eduqas A-Level Digital Technology Unit 4. All rights reserved.\n795: \n796: ---\n797: \n798: <p align=\"center\">\n799:   Built with 🔥 by the LAMPForge team\n800: </p>\n\n(End of file - total 800 lines)\n</content>",
