    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\\\RAEng_Technical_Report_Local_AI_Optimization.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\RAEng_Technical_Report_Local_AI_Optimization.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Hardware-Aware Inference Orchestration for Resource-Constrained Educational Hardware\n2: \n3: **Technical Report & IP Evidence for the Royal Academy of Engineering (RAEng)**\n4: **Programme**: Regional Talent Engines - Stage 2\n5: **Project**: LAMPForge SDTP (Localized Agentic Model Performance Forge)\n6: **Classification**: Deep Tech Research / IP Documentation / Statement of Inventive Step\n7: **Date**: 26 February 2026\n8: **Host Hardware**: HP OMEN 15-ce0xx (2017), Intel i5-7300HQ, 16GB DDR4, GTX 1050 4GB, Windows 10 Pro Build 19045\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## 1. Abstract\n13: \n14: This report documents a programme of deep technical research into the deployment of transformer-class neural networks on consumer-grade hardware that falls below manufacturer-specified minimums. Through a combination of **Native INT4 Quantization**, **Architectural Masquerading**, and **Triple-Tier Inference Fallback**, we demonstrate that a 9-year-old laptop - classified as end-of-life by corporate, EMEA, and APAC IT standards - can perform local AI intent classification at 2.6-second latency without cloud dependency.\n15: \n16: This report presents all findings with full intellectual honesty, clearly distinguishing between what has been implemented, what remains aspirational, and where the boundaries of novelty lie relative to existing tools and prior art.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 2. The Objective Technical Problem\n21: \n22: Current state-of-the-art LLM orchestration systems assume high-performance hardware. Microsoft's own Foundry Local documentation specifies a minimum of **16GB RAM (32GB recommended)** and a \"modern CPU.\" The Phi-4 Educator Blog (Microsoft Tech Community, November 2025) targets **developers with capable machines**, not students on DfE-provisioned hardware.\n23: \n24: Standard UK educational hardware - typically Celeron N4020 processors with 4-8GB RAM and 64GB eMMC storage - is physically incapable of executing frontier reasoning models in their published form. This creates a structural exclusion: students at well-funded schools access local AI; students on DfE \"potato\" hardware cannot.\n25: \n26: > [!IMPORTANT]\n27: > This is not a software bug. It is a market failure driven by misaligned incentives (Section 8).\n28: \n29: ---\n30: \n31: ## 3. What Was Built (Implemented - Verified in Code)\n32: \n33: The following capabilities exist in production code and have been verified through live testing on the host hardware.\n34: \n35: ### 3.1 Native Windows INT4 Quantization\n36: \n37: The Arch-Router-1.5B model (a Qwen2-architecture intent classifier from Katanemo) was quantized from FP16 to INT4 natively on Windows using `optimum-cli` and `onnxruntime-genai`.\n38: \n39: | Metric | Original (FP16) | Optimized (INT4) | Change |\n40: | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n41: | Model Size | 3.5 GB | 1.8 GB | -49% |\n42: | Inference Latency | ~15.0s (est.) | 2.6s (measured) | -5.7x |\n43: | RAM Footprint | ~7.0 GB (est.) | ~2.5 GB (measured) | -64% |\n44: \n45: **What makes this deep tech research**: The quantization itself uses standard tools (prior art exists). The research contribution is the **specific dependency configuration** required to make these tools function on a 7th Gen Kaby Lake CPU running Windows 10 Build 19045 - a configuration that `olive auto-opt` failed silently on, and that required manual version management of `transformers` (4.44.2 → 4.48.2), `torch` (2.4.1), and `onnxruntime-genai` to resolve cascading `DynamicCache` and `Qwen2_5_VL` import errors.\n46: \n47: **Where this is NOT deep tech**: INT4 quantization is a well-published technique (circa 2022-2023). A person skilled in the art could perform it on modern hardware by following Microsoft's documentation. The novelty is not the math - it is the engineering required to make it work on sub-spec hardware where the official tooling fails.\n48: \n49: ### 3.2 Architectural Masquerading\n50: \n51: When the quantized Arch-Router was registered in Foundry Local's `foundry.modelinfo.json` under its real name (`arch-router-1.5b-generic-cpu:4`), the service rejected it:\n52: \n53: > `❌ Model <arch-router-1.5b-generic-cpu:4> was not found in the catalog or local cache.`\n54: \n55: Foundry Local reconciles local metadata against an online Azure AI Model Catalog manifest. If the model ID is not in the remote catalog, the service refuses to initialise the ONNX execution provider - regardless of whether the local files are valid.\n56: \n57: **The Inventive Step**: We discovered that the Arch-Router-1.5B shares **complete architectural parity** with Qwen2-1.5B (identical RMSNorm, RoPE, GQA, SwiGLU layer structure). By placing the forged INT4 weights into the cache directory of the catalogued model (`Microsoft\\qwen2.5-1.5b-instruct-generic-cpu-4\\v4\\`), the service loaded the Arch-Router under the Qwen identity.\n58: \n59: The inference engine validates the **model name**, not the **weight tensors**. This is not documented by Microsoft. It was discovered through empirical engineering after the official registration path failed.\n60: \n61: **Why this qualifies as an inventive step**: Microsoft's official documentation describes a workflow for custom models via Olive compilation and registration. This official path was attempted and failed (silent failure, no error output). The Masquerade is a **novel utilisation of architectural compatibility** that achieves the same goal through a method the vendor did not design, document, or intend.\n62: \n63: **Honest limitation**: This technique works only within architecture families that share identical tensor structures. It does not work across incompatible architectures (e.g., Phi, Gemma, MoE models). See Section 6 for generalisability analysis.\n64: \n65: ### 3.3 Triple-Tier Inference Fallback\n66: \n67: The fallback chain is implemented in `forge-ai.ts`:\n68: \n69: 1. **Tier 1**: `tryFoundryLocal()` - Local CPU inference via masqueraded Arch-Router\n70: 2. **Tier 2**: `tryGroq()` - Cloud fallback using Llama 3.3 70B\n71: 3. **Tier 3**: `tryCerebras()` - Cloud fallback using Llama 3.1 70B\n72: \n73: If any tier fails (HTTP error or timeout), the system catches the error and attempts the next tier. A student never sees a \"Connection Error\" as long as at least one tier is operational.\n74: \n75: **Where this IS deep tech**: The combination of local masqueraded inference with automatic cloud failover for educational hardware is, to our knowledge, not implemented by any other system. Ollama does not fall back to cloud APIs. vLLM does not target consumer hardware. Microsoft's Foundry tutorial has no fallback mechanism.\n76: \n77: **Where this is NOT deep tech**: Try/catch error handling and HTTP fallback are standard programming patterns. The individual mechanism is not novel; the **integration for the specific problem domain** (DfE educational hardware) is what constitutes the contribution.\n78: \n79: ---\n80: \n81: ## 4. What Was NOT Built (Aspirational - Not Yet Implemented)\n82: \n83: Full intellectual honesty requires clearly stating what does not yet exist in code.\n84: \n85: | Claimed Capability | Status | Gap |\n86: | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n87: | **Active VRAM/RAM Management** | ❌ Not implemented | No `os.freemem()` check before inference |\n88: | **Dynamic GPU↔CPU Layer Shifting** | ❌ Not possible | This technology does not exist in any runtime (ORT, llama.cpp, vLLM) as a dynamic, mid-inference capability |\n89: | **\"Sovereign Pedagogical VM\" / Sandbox** | ❌ Not implemented | Foundry Local runs as a standard Windows process with full user-level permissions |\n90: | **Hardware-Aware Model Selection** | ❌ Not implemented | The system does not detect available RAM and select an optimal model |\n91: | **Proactive Tier-Switching** | ❌ Not implemented | Fallback is reactive (after failure), not proactive (before failure) |\n92: \n93: > [!CAUTION]\n94: > These capabilities are architecturally feasible and on the development roadmap, but they must NOT be claimed as \"implemented\" in any RAEng or patent submission until code exists and is verified.\n95: \n96: ### 4.1 Implementation Pathway\n97: \n98: The proactive RAM monitoring is the most immediately implementable gap (~15 minutes):\n99: \n100: ```typescript\n101: // Proposed addition to forge-ai.ts\n102: const freeMemGB = require('os').freemem() / (1024 ** 3);\n103: if (freeMemGB < 3.0) {\n104:   onProgress?.(`Low RAM (${freeMemGB.toFixed(1)}GB) - routing to cloud`);\n105:   // Skip local inference, proceed to tryGroq()\n106: }\n107: ```\n108: \n109: The Hardware-Aware Model Selection requires a tiered model registry (~2-3 hours):\n110: \n111: ```\n112: RAM ≥ 12GB free  → Phi-4 (14B, full reasoning)\n113: RAM ≥ 5GB free   → Phi-4-mini (3.8B, good reasoning)\n114: RAM ≥ 3GB free   → Phi-3.5-mini (3.8B, lightweight)\n115: RAM ≥ 2GB free   → Qwen2.5-0.5b (500M, basic generation)\n116: RAM < 2GB        → Skip local → route to Groq cloud\n117: ```\n118: \n119: ---\n120: \n121: ## 5. The Host Hardware: Why This Machine Matters\n122: \n123: The HP OMEN 15-ce0xx (2017) with an Intel i5-7300HQ (7th Gen Kaby Lake) is classified as follows in 2026:\n124: \n125: | Context | Classification |\n126: | :--- | :--- |\n127: | DfE (UK Education) | Below minimum procurement spec (8th Gen+ required) |\n128: | Corporate UK ITAM | End-of-Life (typical 5-year refresh; this machine is 9 years) |\n129: | EMEA Enterprise | Decommissioned / WEEE recycling queue |\n130: | AI/ML Industry | Below minimum (RTX 3060 / Apple M1 typically expected) |\n131: \n132: ### 5.1 Why Quantization Succeeded on This Hardware\n133: \n134: The INT4 quantization process required:\n135: - **~6-8GB peak RAM** during conversion - fits within 16GB physical RAM\n136: - **AVX2 instruction set** for vectorised scale/zero-point calculations - supported by i5-7300HQ\n137: \n138: The Windows virtual memory subsystem (Total Virtual Memory: 34.1GB = 16GB physical + 18.2GB page file) was available as a safety net but was **likely not the critical enabler**. The 12-minute forge duration suggests the process ran primarily in physical RAM; heavy disk paging would have extended this to hours.\n139: \n140: **Honest assessment**: Virtual memory paging is a 34-year-old technology (Windows 3.1, 1992). It is not novel and should not be claimed as part of the inventive step.\n141: \n142: ### 5.2 Minimum Viable Forge Hardware\n143: \n144: | Device | Could Forge (Quantize)? | Could Run Inference? |\n145: | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n146: | HP OMEN i5-7300HQ, 16GB (yours) | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes (2.6s) |\n147: | DfE Celeron N4020, 4GB | ❌ No (insufficient RAM + no AVX2) | ⚠️ Maybe (60s+) |\n148: | Raspberry Pi 5, 8GB | ❌ No (ARM, no AVX2) | ⚠️ Maybe (45s+, different toolchain) |\n149: | Raspberry Pi 4, 4GB | ❌ No | ❌ No (OOM) |\n150: \n151: Your OMEN is the **absolute minimum viable forge environment** for this technique on x86 Windows. One tier lower (8GB RAM or no AVX2) and the forge fails.\n152: \n153: ---\n154: \n155: ## 6. Generalisability Analysis: Architectural Convergence\n156: \n157: The Masquerade works only within **architecture families** - models sharing identical layer structures (RMSNorm, RoPE, GQA, SwiGLU). We analysed the top 50 models by pull count on Ollama's public library (February 2026) and the complete Foundry Local catalog (26 models).\n158: \n159: ### 6.1 Ollama Ecosystem (Pull-Weighted)\n160: \n161: | Architecture Family | Combined Pulls | % of Ecosystem | Masquerade Compatible? |\n162: | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n163: | Llama/Qwen Recipe | ~350M+ | **~67%** | ✅ Yes |\n164: | Gemma family | ~50M | ~10% | ❌ No |\n165: | Phi family | ~25M | ~5% | ❌ No |\n166: | MoE models | ~10M | ~2% | ❌ No |\n167: | GPT-variant | ~7M | ~1.5% | ❌ No |\n168: | Others / Embeddings | ~70M | ~14% | Mixed / N/A |\n169: \n170: ### 6.2 Foundry Local Catalog\n171: \n172: | Family | Models | Masquerade Target? |\n173: | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n174: | Qwen2.5 variants | 8 | ✅ Primary targets |\n175: | DeepSeek R1 distills | 3 | ✅ Qwen-based underneath |\n176: | Mistral | 2 | ✅ Llama-adjacent |\n177: | Phi variants | 7 | ❌ Different architecture (but natively catalogued - no masquerade needed) |\n178: | GPT-OSS | 1 | ❌ Different architecture |\n179: | Whisper (audio) | 5 | N/A |\n180: \n181: ### 6.3 Trend Analysis\n182: \n183: Architecture convergence is **accelerating**. The \"Llama Recipe\" (RMSNorm + RoPE + GQA + SwiGLU) has become the de facto standard for open-source LLMs. Key milestones:\n184: \n185: - **2023**: Llama 2 open-sourced - the \"Recipe\" is born\n186: - **2024**: Qwen2, Yi, DeepSeek adopt the same architecture - convergence reaches ~60%\n187: - **2025**: DeepSeek-R1 distils its 671B MoE model back into dense Qwen-compatible architectures for edge deployment - convergence reaches ~67%\n188: \n189: **Counter-trend**: The W3C WebNN standard (Candidate Recommendation) may eliminate catalog restrictions entirely by enabling in-browser ONNX inference. If WebNN matures, the Masquerade transitions from a deployment necessity to a historical contribution. The IP value window is **now**.\n190: \n191: ### 6.4 The Phi Gap: Not a Problem, an Opportunity\n192: \n193: Phi models (Phi-3, Phi-3.5, Phi-4) are architecturally incompatible with the Masquerade. However, they are **already natively catalogued in Foundry Local** and therefore do not require masquerading. The opportunity is different: **Hardware-Aware Model Selection** - automatically choosing the right Phi variant based on detected system resources (see Section 4.1). Microsoft's Educator Blog assumes 16GB+ RAM; DfE hardware has 4-8GB. Nobody is building the bridge.\n194: \n195: ---\n196: \n197: ## 7. Competitive Landscape\n198: \n199: ### 7.1 Honest Assessment\n200: \n201: | System | Local Inference? | Cloud Fallback? | Hardware-Aware? | DfE Target? |\n202: | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n203: | **vLLM** | ✅ (GPU datacenter) | ❌ | ❌ (assumes 80GB VRAM) | ❌ |\n204: | **Ollama / llama.cpp** | ✅ (CPU/GPU consumer) | ❌ | Static layer offloading only | ❌ |\n205: | **Microsoft Foundry Local** | ✅ (Catalogued models only) | ❌ | Auto-selects CPU/GPU/NPU variant | ❌ |\n206: | **Microsoft Educator Blog** | ✅ (Phi-4 tutorial) | ❌ | ❌ (assumes 16GB+ RAM) | Partially |\n207: | **LAMPForge (this project)** | ✅ (Masqueraded + native) | ✅ (Groq + Cerebras) | Roadmap | ✅ |\n208: \n209: **Honest caveat on Ollama**: The claim that \"Ollama crashes if Chrome eats 2GB RAM\" is overstated. Ollama uses `mmap` for weight loading, which the OS can page out gracefully. It may slow severely but rarely hard-crashes from memory pressure. The more accurate distinction is that Ollama has **no cloud fallback mechanism** - if local inference fails or is too slow, the user gets nothing.\n210: \n211: ### 7.2 Why Nobody Else Is Doing This (Incentive Structure)\n212: \n213: This analysis draws on the framework articulated by Tristan Harris regarding structural incentive misalignment in technology platforms.\n214: \n215: | Actor | Incentive | Result |\n216: | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n217: | **Cloud Providers** (OpenAI, Google, Anthropic) | Revenue per API call | Will never optimise local inference; local failure pushes users to cloud |\n218: | **Hardware Vendors** (NVIDIA, Intel, Qualcomm) | Revenue from new silicon | Will never optimise for 2017 hardware; obsolescence drives sales |\n219: | **Open Source** (Ollama, llama.cpp) | Built by enthusiasts with modern hardware | Don't experience the DfE problem; no contributor has tested on a Celeron N4020 |\n220: | **Education Sector** (DfE, Schools) | Want AI in classrooms | Have no AI engineers; buy whatever Microsoft/Google sell them |\n221: \n222: The market gap exists because it is **unprofitable for every incumbent**. The only actor with both the incentive (educational equity) and the technical capacity (engineering skill on constrained hardware) is an independent engineer operating outside all four incentive structures.\n223: \n224: ---\n225: \n226: ## 8. Statement of Inventive Step (For Mathys & Squire / UKIPO)\n227: \n228: ### 8.1 The Technical Effect\n229: \n230: This is not \"pure software\" or a \"mathematical method as such\" (Patents Act 1977, s.1(2)). Per *Symbian v Comptroller* [2008] EWCA Civ 1066, software that makes a computer **operate more efficiently** produces a patentable technical effect.\n231: \n232: Our method makes a computer that **could not run** a 1.5-billion parameter transformer model **now able to run it** at interactive latency. The computer itself operates differently as a result.\n233: \n234: ### 8.2 The Composite Claim\n235: \n236: > *\"A method for resilient AI inference on resource-constrained hardware, comprising:*\n237: >\n238: > *(a) Targeted precision reduction (INT4 quantization) of transformer-class neural networks to a bit-width compatible with the device's instruction set architecture;*\n239: >\n240: > *(b) Architectural masquerading - a novel utilisation of structural parity between transformer architectures (RMSNorm/RoPE/GQA) to deploy non-catalogued models on catalog-restricted inference runtimes under a recognised model identity;*\n241: >\n242: > *(c) Multi-tier inference fallback ensuring service continuity when local resources are insufficient;*\n243: >\n244: > *(d) The combined system producing a technical effect of hardware life extension, enabling AI-powered applications on devices below the vendor's minimum specification.\"*\n245: \n246: ### 8.3 Novelty Assessment\n247: \n248: | Element | Novel? | Prior Art? | Patentable Alone? |\n249: | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n250: | INT4 Quantization | ❌ | Widely published since 2022 | No |\n251: | Architectural Masquerading | ✅ | No known prior art | Weak alone (Foundry-specific) |\n252: | Triple-Tier Fallback | ❌ | Fallback patterns exist | No |\n253: | **The Combined Method** | ✅ | No known prior art for this integration | **Yes - defensible** |\n254: \n255: ### 8.4 Comparison to Official Microsoft Path\n256: \n257: | | Official Olive/Foundry Path | LAMPForge Path |\n258: | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n259: | Model Freedom | Restricted to Olive-compiled ONNX + catalog-listed models | Unlimited within architecturally compatible families (~67%) |\n260: | Speed to Frontier | Weeks-to-months (wait for catalog update) | ~30 minutes (quantise + masquerade) |\n261: | Sub-spec Stability | Manufacturer's \"best effort\" (silent failures on constrained hardware) | Guaranteed via triple-tier fallback |\n262: \n263: ---\n264: \n265: ## 9. Professional Classification\n266: \n267: ### 9.1 SFIA (Skills Framework for the Information Age)\n268: \n269: This work operates at **SFIA Level 5 (Ensure, Advise)** with elements of **Level 6 (Initiate, Influence)**:\n270: \n271: - **Emerging Technology Monitoring (EMRG)**: Identified and exploited architectural convergence across transformer families\n272: - **Systems Design (DESN)**: Designed a multi-tier failover architecture with hardware-aware routing\n273: - **Programming/Software Development (PROG)**: Manufactured binary artifacts (INT4 ONNX weights) and integrated them into a production pipeline\n274: \n275: ### 9.2 Bloom's Taxonomy\n276: \n277: | Level | Evidence |\n278: | :--- | :--- |\n279: | **1. Remember** | Recalled ONNX, Foundry, and quantization tool capabilities |\n280: | **2. Understand** | Understood why Foundry's catalog rejected the Arch-Router |\n281: | **3. Apply** | Applied INT4 quantization using `optimum-cli` and `onnxruntime-genai` |\n282: | **4. Analyse** | Analysed Foundry error logs to identify catalog enforcement as the root cause |\n283: | **5. Evaluate** | Evaluated that the official Olive path was non-viable on constrained hardware; evaluated that WSL networking was too unreliable for production |\n284: | **6. Create** | **Synthesised the Architectural Masquerade** - a deployment method not documented by Microsoft, derived from empirical analysis of architectural parity |\n285: \n286: ---\n287: \n288: ## 10. Behavioural Economics: The £6 USB Stick\n289: \n290: If the Hardware-Aware Model Selection (Section 4.1) is implemented:\n291: \n292: | Component | Cost |\n293: | :--- | :--- |\n294: | USB 3.0 Stick (32GB, exFAT) | **£6** |\n295: | Pre-loaded INT4 model + PWA app | **£0** |\n296: | Browser (Edge/Chrome, pre-installed on DfE hardware) | **£0** |\n297: | Cloud API keys (Groq/Cerebras free tier) | **£0** |\n298: \n299: **Total cost to a student: £6.** Total installation: plug in USB, open browser. Total admin permissions: zero. Total data exfiltration during local operation: zero.\n300: \n301: This reduces the **action cost** of local AI from \"£1,500 GPU workstation + IT admin approval + cloud API subscription\" to \"a trip to Tesco.\" The entire economic barrier becomes a commodity consumer purchase already on the approved school supplies list.\n302: \n303: ---\n304: \n305: ## 11. Future Direction: Browser-First via WebNN\n306: \n307: The W3C WebNN standard (Candidate Recommendation, supported in Edge via DirectML) enables in-browser ONNX inference with automatic hardware dispatch (CPU/GPU/NPU). This would:\n308: \n309: - ✅ Eliminate the Masquerade entirely (no catalog in the browser)\n310: - ✅ Provide sandboxing for free (browser origin isolation = \"Sovereign Pedagogical VM\")\n311: - ✅ Enable zero-install deployment from USB\n312: - ⚠️ Requires WebNN maturation (currently limited model support)\n313: \n314: The Masquerade is a **transitional innovation** - valuable now, historically interesting later. The broader contribution (Hardware-Aware Orchestration for educational hardware) persists regardless of which runtime executes the inference.\n315: \n316: ---\n317: \n318: ## 12. Analogues in the Field\n319: \n320: The approach is conceptually analogous to **Unsloth** (YC-backed, 2024), which rewrites CUDA training kernels to achieve 2-5x speedups by operating outside the constraints of the Hugging Face Trainer \"establishment\" tooling.\n321: \n322: | | Unsloth | LAMPForge |\n323: | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n324: | Establishment tool bypassed | Hugging Face Trainer | Microsoft Foundry catalog |\n325: | The constraint | Training is too slow/expensive | Inference is impossible on DfE hardware |\n326: | The solution | Rewrote CUDA kernels | Rewrote the deployment pipeline |\n327: | The result | 2-5x faster fine-tuning | Inference where there was none |\n328: \n329: **Honest distinction**: Unsloth is a production-grade tool with thousands of users and venture capital funding. LAMPForge is a verified proof-of-concept on a single machine. The intellectual approach is analogous; the scale and maturity are not.\n330: \n331: ---\n332: \n333: *End of Report*\n334: *All claims marked ✅ have been verified through live testing on the host hardware.*\n335: *All claims marked ❌ are clearly identified as not yet implemented.*\n\n(End of file - total 335 lines)\n</content>",
