      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\docs\\RUNTIME-ARCHITECTURE.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # LAMPForge Runtime Architecture\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: The LAMPForge runtime is a self-contained LAMP stack that runs in Windows user-space. It requires no administrator privileges, no system-level service installation, and no modification of system PATH or registry outside the user's own `%LOCALAPPDATA%`. The learner's machine is unmodified at the system level.\n6: \n7: ---\n8: \n9: ## Component Choices\n10: \n11: ### Why MySQL (Not MariaDB)\n12: \n13: The WJEC specification names \"RDBMS\" and all WJEC ecosystem teaching materials reference MySQL. Generated PHP uses `mysqli_connect` and `PDO(\"mysql:...\")` - patterns immediately legible to examiners. MySQL Workbench provides a free ERD designer with no MariaDB equivalent. phpMyAdmin has \"My\" (MySQL) in its name.\n14: \n15: MariaDB is a professional career-stage concern (open-source stewardship, Galera clustering). Pedagogical tools optimise for specification legibility, not operational concerns. LAMPForge uses MySQL 8.0.x.\n16: \n17: ### Why Caddy (Not Apache)\n18: \n19: Apache requires system-level service installation on Windows and is visible to the operating system's service manager. Caddy:\n20: \n21: - Runs as a standard user process with no elevation\n22: - Binds only to `127.0.0.1` (configurable)\n23: - Has zero external configuration file format complexity\n24: - Handles FastCGI (PHP-CGI) natively with a three-line config block\n25: - Is a single static binary with no DLL dependencies\n26: \n27: The assessor sees the PHP application. They do not see the web server. Caddy is deliberately invisible - which is exactly correct for a pedagogical tool.\n28: \n29: ### PHP-CGI\n30: \n31: PHP-CGI (not PHP-FPM, not mod_php) is used because:\n32: - It runs as a plain user-space process\n33: - Caddy's `php_fastcgi` directive connects to it directly\n34: - No process manager (like FPM's pool configuration) is required\n35: - The Windows PHP build ships `php-cgi.exe` as a first-class binary\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: ## Directory Layout\n40: \n41: ```\n42: %LOCALAPPDATA%\\LAMPForgeRuntime\\\n43:   bundles\\\n44:     lampforge-runtime-win-x64@1.0.0\\        ← immutable bundle (read-only after install)\n45:       mysql\\bin\\mysqld.exe\n46:       php\\php-cgi.exe\n47:       php\\php.ini\n48:       caddy\\caddy.exe\n49:       phpmyadmin\\                            ← standard phpMyAdmin release\n50:       openvscode\\\n51:   state\\                                     ← mutable state (learner data lives here)\n52:     mysql\\data\\                              ← MySQL datadir\n53:     mysql\\my.ini                             ← generated config (from my.ini.template)\n54:     www\\                                     ← student's project files\n55:     phpmyadmin-config\\\n56:       config.inc.php                         ← generated (from config.inc.php.template)\n57:     logs\\\n58:       mysql.log\n59:       caddy.log\n60:       php-cgi.log\n61:   config\\\n62:     current.json                             ← active bundle pointer\n63:     credentials.json                         ← generated MySQL root password (not committed)\n64:     runtime-endpoints.json                   ← URLs for PDE to consume\n65: ```\n66: \n67: ### State / Binary Separation\n68: \n69: The `bundles/` directory is **immutable after install**. The supervisor never writes to it. All mutable data - MySQL data files, log files, project files, generated credentials - lives in `state/` and `config/`.\n70: \n71: This separation has two consequences:\n72: \n73: 1. **Rollback is safe**: switching `config/current.json` to point at an older bundle version does not require touching any learner data.\n74: 2. **Backup is simple**: backing up `state/` and `config/` is sufficient to preserve all learner work.\n75: \n76: ---\n77: \n78: ## Side-by-Side Versioning Strategy\n79: \n80: Multiple bundle versions can be installed simultaneously. Each bundle lives in its own subdirectory under `bundles/`, named `lampforge-runtime-{platform}@{version}`.\n81: \n82: ```\n83: bundles/\n84:   lampforge-runtime-win-x64@1.0.0\\   ← previous version (kept for rollback)\n85:   lampforge-runtime-win-x64@1.1.0\\   ← current version\n86: ```\n87: \n88: The active bundle is determined by `config/current.json`:\n89: \n90: ```json\n91: {\n92:   \"active\": \"lampforge-runtime-win-x64@1.1.0\",\n93:   \"platform\": \"win-x64\"\n94: }\n95: ```\n96: \n97: Switching versions is an atomic file write. No process migration is required - the supervisor restarts with the new binary paths on next start.\n98: \n99: ---\n100: \n101: ## Update Algorithm\n102: \n103: ```\n104: 1. PDE calls POST /update on supervisor\n105: 2. Supervisor fetches registry index from GitHub Releases\n106: 3. Supervisor compares registry version against active bundle version\n107: 4. If update available:\n108:    a. Download bundle ZIP to temp directory\n109:    b. Verify SHA-256 hash against registry entry\n110:    c. Unpack to bundles/{platform}@{new_version}/\n111:    d. Write new config/current.json pointing at new version\n112:    e. Stop all services\n113:    f. Start all services with new binary paths\n114:    g. Run health check (GET /status - all services must report \"running\")\n115:    h. If health check fails: revert config/current.json to previous version, restart old version\n116: 5. Report result to PDE via response body\n117: ```\n118: \n119: SHA-256 verification happens before unpacking. A corrupted or tampered download never reaches the filesystem.\n120: \n121: Rollback is automatic on health check failure. The previous bundle is never deleted until a subsequent successful update completes.\n122: \n123: ---\n124: \n125: ## Security Model\n126: \n127: ### 127.0.0.1 Binding Only\n128: \n129: All services bind to `127.0.0.1` (localhost loopback) only:\n130: \n131: - MySQL: `bind-address = 127.0.0.1`\n132: - Caddy: `http://127.0.0.1:{http_port}`\n133: - phpMyAdmin: served by Caddy on `127.0.0.1:{phpmyadmin_port}`\n134: - Supervisor API: `127.0.0.1:9000`\n135: \n136: No service is reachable from other machines on the network. This is enforced in the configuration templates, not just as a recommendation.\n137: \n138: ### Generated Credentials\n139: \n140: MySQL root password is generated at first-run using a cryptographically random 32-character hex string. It is written to `config/credentials.json` which is:\n141: \n142: - Never committed to source control (`.gitignore` entry)\n143: - Never included in PDE-generated output\n144: - Read by the supervisor at startup only\n145: - Not transmitted over any network interface\n146: \n147: ### No 0.0.0.0\n148: \n149: The configuration templates explicitly do not use `0.0.0.0` (all interfaces). This is a hard constraint, not a default. Templates use `{{mysql_host}}` and `{{http_host}}` placeholders which the supervisor resolves to `127.0.0.1`.\n150: \n151: ---\n152: \n153: ## Compatibility Contract\n154: \n155: ### runtimeApiVersion\n156: \n157: The manifest schema includes a `runtimeApiVersion` field (currently `1`). This is an integer that increments when breaking changes are made to:\n158: \n159: - The supervisor API contract\n160: - The configuration template format\n161: - The state directory layout\n162: \n163: The PDE checks `runtimeApiVersion` before issuing supervisor API calls. If the PDE's expected version does not match the running supervisor's version, the PDE shows a \"Runtime update required\" message.\n164: \n165: ### minPdeVersion / maxPdeVersion\n166: \n167: Each bundle version declares the minimum PDE version required to use it (`minPdeVersion`). Registry entries may also declare `maxPdeVersion` to prevent old PDE versions from downloading incompatible bundles.\n168: \n169: The PDE's own version (from `package.json`) is checked against the bundle's `minPdeVersion` before activation.\n170: \n171: ---\n172: \n173: ## Supervisor Process Model\n174: \n175: The supervisor is a small native Windows executable (Go binary, single file, no DLL dependencies) that:\n176: \n177: 1. Reads `config/current.json` to determine active bundle paths\n178: 2. Renders configuration templates (`my.ini`, `Caddyfile`, `php.ini`, `config.inc.php`) to `state/`\n179: 3. Starts MySQL, then PHP-CGI, then Caddy as child processes\n180: 4. Monitors child process health via periodic port checks\n181: 5. Restarts crashed child processes automatically\n182: 6. Exposes a REST API on `127.0.0.1:9000`\n183: 7. Logs all activity to `state/logs/`\n184: \n185: The supervisor itself runs as a plain user process - no Windows service, no UAC prompt.\n\n(End of file - total 185 lines)\n</content>",
